Revision history for Lilith

4.0.0	unreleased
		 - Add MITRE ATT&CK tactic/technique as virtual Suricata dashboard
		   dimensions, read from the alert.metadata a ruleset (e.g.
		   Emerging Threats) tags on, with the underscored names spaced out
		   for display and backed by partial expression indexes in schema
		   version 8 (partial because MITRE is present on only a fraction
		   of alerts). The default board gains a tactic pie beside the
		   alerts-over-time chart (empty where the ruleset does not tag
		   MITRE).
		 - Give the top-values and alerts-over-time widgets a "measure":
		   besides counting rows they can sum/average a numeric column or
		   count distinct values, via a per-table catalog
		   (GET /api/dashboard/measures over Lilith::Stats->measures). This
		   turns the Suricata flow byte/packet counters into top-talker and
		   bandwidth panels and the ports into port-scan / fan-out panels,
		   and adds average/max malscore for CAPE. The default board gains
		   a bandwidth chart plus top-talkers-by-bytes and fan-out panels,
		   and bar/axis values are shown compactly (1.5K, 3.2M).
		 - Ship a fuller Suricata-shaped default dashboard (alerts over
		   time, top classifications/signatures, severity and app-protocol
		   pies, top source/destination IPs and ports, per-sensor, and
		   source countries) and document the dashboard, its widget types,
		   and the recipe panels per table in docs/dashboard.md.
		 - Make the dashboard panels configurable widgets rather than a
		   fixed set. An "Add widget" picker builds timeseries, top-values
		   (any column -- including a virtual "severity" read from the raw
		   EVE for suricata, its 1-4 numbers shown as High/Medium/Low/
		   Informational and ordered by that rank, backed by an expression
		   index in schema version 7 -- drawn as a bar or pie, showing 1-50
		   values), and source-country
		   widgets; each has a gear to
		   reconfigure and an x to remove, and the whole set drag/resizes
		   and persists as before. The saved layout now stores each
		   widget's type and config (not just its position), sanitized
		   server-side against a type/config whitelist. A new
		   GET /api/dashboard/columns endpoint (over Lilith::Stats->columns)
		   drives the config pickers from the same whitelist the API
		   validates against. A fresh or reset board starts from a
		   built-in default widget set.
		 - Make the dashboard panels draggable and resizable with
		   Gridstack (vendored), laid out on a 12-column grid. The layout
		   is saved to a new dashboards table (schema version 6) as a
		   global "default" board -- the web UI is unauthenticated, so
		   boards are shared rather than per-user -- via the
		   GET/POST /api/dashboard/layout endpoints and Lilith's
		   dashboard_get/dashboard_save. A "Reset layout" button restores
		   the built-in positions.
		 - Add a web dashboard at /dashboard: stat cards (total,
		   escalated, unique sources, unique signatures/targets, busiest
		   sensor), an alerts over time chart stacked by
		   classification/target, six per-table top-N charts
		   (classification/signature/program/src+dest IP/dest port/app
		   proto/level/facility/target/pkg/malscore/url host), and a top
		   source countries chart resolved through the GeoIP databases,
		   with a table and time-range selector. Backed by
		   Lilith::Web::Controller::Dashboard and the
		   /api/dashboard/{summary,top,timeseries,countries} JSON endpoints
		   over Lilith::Stats, drawn with a vendored Chart.js. A "Show
		   GPCD" checkbox (off by default) toggles whether Generic Protocol
		   Command Decode alerts are included. A Dashboard (and Search)
		   link were added to the navbar.
		 - Add Lilith::Stats, the dashboard's aggregation layer: total,
		   distinct, top, and (bucketed, optionally grouped) timeseries
		   over the suricata/sagan/cape alert tables, windowed on
		   timestamp (or stop for cape) and leaning on the version-5
		   indexes. Table/column/bucket names are whitelisted and the
		   window/limit are integer-checked, so request parameters can be
		   passed straight through. Reachable as $lilith->stats.
		 - Fix the migration fixture directories never installing. The
		   share/fixtures/<version>/conf dirs were kept by a .exists
		   placeholder, but ExtUtils::Install hardcodes skipping that
		   reserved MakeMaker marker name, so the dirs never reached the
		   installed share tree and a non-root `lilith migrate` died
		   trying to mkdir them under the root-owned share. Renamed the
		   placeholder to "keep" so the directories install.
		 - Add lilith deploy / migrate / schema_version commands wrapping
		   DBIx::Class::Migration, so the schema is installed and upgraded
		   with the same CLI and config file as everything else rather
		   than by calling dbic-migration by hand. schema_version reports
		   the deployed vs expected version and whether work is pending.
		 - Add search / dashboard indexes (schema version 5). The alert
		   tables previously carried only their primary key, so search()
		   and any aggregation seq-scanned the whole table. Add the time
		   column (timestamp, or stop for cape) plus composite
		   (column, time) btrees over the top filters per table
		   (classification, src_ip, sid; malscore/target for cape) so
		   filtered "newest N" queries and time-windowed GROUP BYs use an
		   index instead. Conservative set -- other cuts and a BRIN on the
		   time column can be added per deployment.
		 - Add mojo_lilith_receiver (Lilith::Receiver), a Mojolicious daemon
		   that ingests pushed alert rows. A remote sensor parses its own
		   EVE stream and POSTs each parse_eve row as JSON to
		   POST /eve/:table, so sensors need no database credentials. The
		   body is validated against the table's column set and inserted via
		   the new shared Lilith::insert_alert; id, escalations, and
		   auto_escalated cannot be set by a caller and a body carrying them
		   is rejected.
		 - Receiver API keys are stored in the database (schema version 4,
		   new receiver_apikeys table) as their SHA-256, managed with the
		   lilith receiver_key_create/list/get/update/delete commands. A key
		   can be scoped to a set of client IPs/subnets and to a set of
		   instance names; instance patterns may use the '*' and '?'
		   wildcards (e.g. foo-*). Behind a reverse proxy set
		   MOJO_REVERSE_PROXY=1 so the client IP scoping works.
		 - Rename init/ to rc/ and split it into rc/freebsd/ and
		   rc/systemd/ (the generic cron entry stays at rc/). Add boot
		   scripts for the Mojolicious daemons: FreeBSD rc.d scripts
		   rc/freebsd/mojo_lilith and rc/freebsd/mojo_lilith_receiver and
		   systemd units rc/systemd/mojo_lilith.service and
		   rc/systemd/mojo_lilith_receiver.service.
		 - Add a escalation system to the web frontend. Escalation targets
		   are stored in SQL (schema version 3, new escalation_targets and
		   escalations tables) and each has a pluggable type; a type is a
		   module under Lilith::Escalate::Type:: (Webhook, Email, and
		   Syslog ship with the dist) and extra namespaces may be added
		   via escalation_type_namespaces in the config. The web UI gets a
		   /escalation management page (targets are created/edited via a
		   form generated from the type's config_fields spec, with a per
		   target test button), an Escalate button + escalation history on
		   the event view, and a "E" badge on escalated events in search
		   results. Every escalation attempt is recorded with its status
		   and the raw JSON payload actually sent, including attempts
		   refused before a send (unknown or disabled target), and the
		   target's name is snapshotted per attempt so history stays
		   readable after a target is deleted. The alert tables gain a
		   escalations bigint[] column holding the escalation IDs for
		   each row, appended in the same transaction as the escalations
		   insert, so anything reading the alert tables can trivially
		   see if/how many times a alert has been escalated without
		   querying the escalations table. All of it is gated
		   behind escalation_enable (off by default) and the sends run in
		   a subprocess so the web server's event loop is not blocked.
		 - lilith CLI: new escalation actions. esc escalates a event to
		   targets given by ID or name (--to, --note, --by; exits
		   non-zero if any target failed), esc_history prints the
		   escalations for a event, esc_types lists the installed types
		   with their config fields, and esc_targets /esc_target_get /
		   esc_target_create / esc_target_update / esc_target_delete /
		   esc_target_test manage targets, with config given as repeated
		   --set key=value items. The escalation actions are not gated
		   by escalation_enable, as that exists for the unauthenticated
		   web UI; the CLI already holds the DB credentials.
		 - Add automatic escalation. A new auto_escalations table (still
		   schema version 3) holds rules as a JSON match/actions DSL;
		   Lilith::AutoEscalate validates a rule and compiles its match
		   into a Rule::Engine ruleset. auto_escalate() evaluates the
		   enabled rules against alerts ingested within a window and,
		   for each match, escalates the alert to the rule's targets via
		   the existing escalate(), so auto escalations share the same
		   audit trail and per-row escalations array. Each alert gains a
		   auto_escalated timestamp so it is considered exactly once;
		   rules are evaluated in priority order and a stop_on_match rule
		   halts later rules for that alert. The lilith CLI gets an
		   auto_escalate action (with --dry-run and --tables) meant to be
		   run periodically, plus ae_list / ae_get / ae_create /
		   ae_update / ae_delete to manage rules. A systemd service +
		   timer and a cron example for running auto_escalate every few
		   minutes ship under rc/. The web UI gets a /auto_escalation
		   page for managing rules: a visual builder for the match tree
		   (nested ALL/ANY/NOT groups of field/op/value tests) with a
		   "Advanced (JSON)" toggle for editing the raw DSL, and a live
		   dry-run preview against recent alerts that never sends. Its
		   gating is two tiered: the page and its read/preview endpoints
		   follow escalation_enable, while creating/editing/deleting
		   rules additionally requires the new auto_escalation_manage_enable
		   (off by default, so a saved rule can not be changed from the
		   web UI unless explicitly opted in); with it off the page is
		   read only.
		 - EVE instances are now defined under the [eves.*] table, e.g.
		   [eves.suricata-eve], instead of as plain top-level tables. Old
		   top-level instance tables are ignored, with a warning.
		 - search() now accepts an array for 'class'; positive values are
		   ORed (via an IN) and '!'-negated values are ANDed, with '%'
		   LIKE support per item.
		 - lilith -a search: -c may be given multiple times or as a comma
		   separated list to match/negate several classifications.
		 - web event view: added a "Download PCAP" control that fetches the
		   flow PCAP from a remote Virani instance and streams it back.
		   Remotes are configured as [virani.NAME] tables; the feature is
		   enabled when one or more are present, and the instance matching
		   the alert is pre-selected. The fetch runs in a subprocess so it
		   does not block the web server's event loop. The control also lets
		   you pick which set to pull from (queried live from the remote) or
		   copy a ready-made virani command to run locally on the PCAP box.
		 - web: a "Virani" navbar dropdown opens either a PCAP search for an
		   arbitrary BPF filter and time range, or (when virani_search_enable
		   is on) a browser of the remote's most recent cached searches with
		   per-row cached-PCAP download. The search always builds a copyable
		   local virani command; direct download through the web server is
		   gated by the virani_search_enable config option (off by default).
		 - web: the /api/ipinfo and /api/domaininfo lookups now run their
		   blocking work in a subprocess, so a slow whois/DNS lookup no
		   longer stalls the web server's event loop.
		 - web: an "HTTPS" button under Domain Info (with a port field,
		   default 443) checks https://DOMAIN:PORT/ and shows the HTTP
		   status (and redirect target), per-phase and total timing, whether
		   the cert is expired, whether it validates (full chain + hostname),
		   and as much certificate detail as possible. 5s timeout, 512KB read
		   cap, both noted when hit.
		 - web: a "Mail" button under Domain Info runs a combined SPF / DMARC
		   / DKIM check. SPF shows the v=spf1 record and a summary, plus a
		   Mail::SPF evaluation when an IP is given. DMARC shows the record
		   and parsed policy (via Mail::DMARC, with the organizational-domain
		   tree walk). DKIM shows the public key for a given selector, or
		   probes common selectors when none is supplied, with maximal key
		   detail (type, size, revoked/testing flags, hashes, etc.).
		 - Lilith->run() now warns and skips a malformed EVE instance
		   instead of dying, so one bad entry no longer stops the rest.
		 - search(): fix multi-value numeric filters (src_port, dest_port,
		   gid, sid, rev, size, malscore, task). Multiple terms were ORed
		   instead of ANDed, so e.g. dest_port "!22, !443" matched every
		   row (a 443 row still satisfies "!= 22") and filtered nothing.
		 - search(): the complex "port" and "ip" filters now understand a
		   '!' prefix (and port the <, <=, >, >= operators) and accept
		   several comma separated values. Previously "!22" was passed
		   straight to Postgres as an integer and errored, and "22,80"
		   died as an invalid port. Positive values are ORed across the
		   source/destination columns and items; a negated value is ANDed
		   so it is excluded from both sides.

		 - Add a docs/ dir (architecture, install, configuration, usage,
		   escalation, security, examples) matching the rest of the
		   LilithSec household, and rework the README to a short intro
		   that points at docs/index.md.

		 - Fix the sagan_alerts INSERT listing "proto" twice (with a
		   matching duplicate bind), which PostgreSQL rejects with
		   "column specified more than once"; the Sagan ingest path now
		   inserts the correct 24 columns.

		 - Factor the EVE field extraction out of the run() POE closure
		   into a testable parse_eve() method, with %Lilith::alert_columns
		   as the shared source of truth for each table's column order
		   (so the INSERT and the parsed row cannot drift). Adds
		   t/lilith-parse-eve.t covering Suricata/Sagan/CAPE parsing,
		   including a regression test for the duplicate-proto fix.

3.0.0	2026-06-25/01:00
